		<header>
			
			<h1>Latin American deals concluded, Asian negotiations launched</h1>

			
			<h4>
												04 April 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 2 March 2010 it was announced that Peru had joined Colombia in concluding a bilateral preferential trade agreement with the EU. The agreements with Colombia and Peru are expected to be signed at a summit in Madrid in mid May 2010, with the agreements coming into effect in 2012. The agreement was reached following the resolution of issues related to market access for agricultural products and the resolution of a range of rules-of-origin and intellectual property rights issues. The conclusion of the bilateral agreement with Colombia and Peru follows the earlier abandonment of a regional approach at the Andean Pact level. However the Bolivian government is reported to be considering filing a complaint with the dispute settlement body of the Andean Community, on the grounds that ‘the new trade deal violates Andean regulations’.</p><p>Through this agreement Peru has secured improved access for its sugar, bananas and other fruit and vegetable exports. Press reports claim that once the agreement enters into force, tariffs will be reduced on 99.3% of Peruvian exports to the EU, with 95% of Peruvian agricultural products benefiting from exemption from the payment of import taxes. More details were provided by Trade Commissioner Karel De Gucht in his address to the European Parliament International Trade Committee on 16 March 2010, where he argued that the substantial new market access for bananas and sugar offered to Colombia and Peru was the key driving factor in the conclusion of the agreement. Banana tariffs will be cut to €75/tonne by 2020 (restoring the tariff to the level applied under the import quotas between 2002 and 2005). For sugar, quotas of 62,000 tonnes and 22,000 tonnes have been allocated to Colombia and Peru respectively (with a 3% annual expansion of quotas), an amount equivalent to ‘less than 1% of global EU sugar consumption’. Substantial market access improvements have also been agreed for beef, rice, pork and maize among other products. None of these products are covered by the EU’s GSP+ regime. The quotas for beef and pork are equivalent to less than 0.1% of EU consumption.</p><p>In terms of EU offensive interests Commissioner De Gucht highlighted the benefits to EU food and agricultural exporters under the agreement, pointing out that ‘we have secured access to these markets for our major offensive agricultural products and processed agricultural products, namely: milk powder, cheese, whey, pork meat, cereals, olive oil, wines and spirits’. He maintained that the agreement also respected EU ‘red lines’ in other areas of agricultural trade relations, including with regard to respect for geographical indicators.</p><p>Significantly the Colombia FTA agreement includes a human rights clause, which, while establishing consultative procedures, allows the EU to ‘cancel autonomously and immediately the trade preferences granted under the FTA’ … ‘whenever an essential element of the agreement has been violated’. Commissioner De Gucht maintains that compared to earlier agreements, ‘the threshold for unilateral suspension is significantly lower’. A ‘simple violation’ of an essential element is sufficient to involve a unilateral suspension. It should be noted that for the trade deals to enter into force, they still need to receive parliamentary approval in the signatory countries, with some parliamentary opposition to the deal now emerging in Colombia.</p><p>Early March also saw the launch of EU free-trade agreement negotiations with Singapore, and the agreement in principle to launch EU-Vietnam FTA negotiations. From the EC perspective it is hoped that this will give a new impetus to trade negotiations with ASEAN countries and India. The EC has suggested that the recent meeting between Trade Commissioner De Gucht and the Indian trade minister Anand Sharma has confirmed the determination of both parties ‘to conclude the FTA negotiations ahead of the EU-India summit in October’.</p><p>The end of February 2010 meanwhile saw the prolongation of the ‘exceptional autonomous trade preferences’ granted to countries of the Western Balkans. These non-reciprocal preferential trade arrangements, first set in place in 2000, will not be allowed to run until 31 December 2015.</p>
		
		
