				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The concluding of preferential trade agreement negotiations with Peru and Colombia along with ongoing negotiations with Central American countries (where a total sugar quota of 250,000 tonnes is under discussion) is causing concern in the ACP Caribbean states, firstly because the EU has gone beyond the Geneva deal on bananas in terms of market access improvements for bananas, and secondly because these agreements will eventually allow exporters from Latin American countries the same levels of access to the EU market which Caribbean suppliers now enjoy. There are concerns that developments since December 2009 mark the beginning of new phase in relations between the EU and the ACP Caribbean countries, with traditional Caribbean concerns being set aside in favour of improvements in trade relations with Latin American countries, whose economies are larger and more dynamic than those of the ACP Caribbean states. The forthcoming formulation of the Caribbean-EU Strategy and the summit meeting in May under the Spanish presidency of the EU will provide an opportunity for the EU to address these Caribbean concerns.</p><p>The prolongation of the ‘exceptional autonomous trade preferences’ granted to countries of the Western Balkans for a further five years has raised the question in the minds of some observers of why an extension of non-reciprocal preferences was possible in the case of the Western Balkans in February 2010, when a further extension of non-reciprocal trade preferences for ACP countries from 1 January 2008 was always ruled out by the European Commission. </p><p>In terms of trade negotiations with India, it is understood that getting to grips effectively with SPS issues, which are seen as an increasingly important barrier to trade, is a ‘deal breaker’ for Indian negotiators. There is seen to be little point in securing duty-free access if non-tariff barriers effectively continue to keep Indian products out of or undermine the commercial attractiveness of the EU market. These concerns would appear to have equal relevance for ACP countries, where SPS and food safety standards, alongside the rise of private voluntary standards and the evolution of EU agricultural product quality policy, are seen as creating new barriers to ACP access to EU markets. These concerns could potentially be addressed through the elaboration of a clear and coherent ‘development dimension’ to EU policies in these areas of food safety, agricultural product quality and the functioning of food supply chains. </p>
		</div>
		
